  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a lemon law?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Lemon laws are consumer protection statutes that entitle buyers of defective vehicles to a repair, replacement, or refund if the manufacturer cannot fix a substantial defect within a reasonable number of attempts. All 50 states plus Washington D.C. have some form of lemon law, and the federal Magnuson-Moss Warranty Act provides an additional layer of protection."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How many repair attempts qualify a car as a lemon?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "This varies by state, but common thresholds are 3–4 repair attempts for the same defect, or the vehicle being out of service for 30 or more cumulative days during the warranty period. Some states have a single-attempt standard for safety-related defects. Check your state's specific lemon law for the exact threshold."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does lemon law apply to used cars?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Most state lemon laws apply only to new vehicles purchased with a manufacturer's warranty. However, some states extend coverage to used vehicles still under the original manufacturer's warranty, and a few have specific used-car lemon laws. The federal Magnuson-Moss Warranty Act can apply to used vehicles if the seller provided a written warranty."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can NHTSA complaint data help my lemon law case?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. NHTSA complaint data can demonstrate that your defect is part of a known pattern affecting other vehicles — strengthening the argument that it is a systemic defect, not a one-off issue. If NHTSA has opened an investigation or issued a recall for the same problem, that is strong supporting evidence. Print and attach relevant complaints and investigation documents to your lemon law demand letter."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<Base title={title} description={description}
